# Observability required

Production-ready systems must include observability mechanisms such as logging, metrics, monitoring, tracing, validation checkpoints, and actionable error handling. Systems should be diagnosable, measurable, and operationally maintainable.

Apply this rule when:

- implementing production services
- creating APIs
- modifying data pipelines
- implementing streaming systems
- deploying distributed systems
- reviewing production readiness

## Agent behavior

- Add or extend structured logs with correlation/request/job identifiers; avoid logging secrets or full PII.
- Expose meaningful metrics (latency, errors, throughput, backlog, lag) and traces where the stack supports them; document what to watch in rollout notes or runbooks when applicable.
- Prefer explicit validation checkpoints on critical pipeline steps; surface errors with enough context for on-call action (not generic “failed” only).

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — New service swallows exceptions, prints to stdout only, no request id, no error rate metric

✅ GOOD — Structured logs + correlation id middleware, redacted payloads, error taxonomy, RED-style metrics or platform equivalent, trace propagation on outbound calls
```
